# The complete VSL craft guide for email marketing agencies

**The highest-converting VSL scripts in 2025–2026 follow a predictable architecture.** After analyzing frameworks from Conversionly, Russell Brunson, Sabri Suby, Stefan Georgi, Todd Brown, Jon Benson, and Cole Gordon — plus real-world agency VSL data — a clear consensus emerges: the script matters 10x more than production quality, the mechanism matters more than the promise, and **a well-structured 8–12 minute VSL with three strategically placed CTAs consistently outperforms every other format for booking discovery calls.** This guide covers every element needed to write a VSL that converts from day one.

---

## 1. The master VSL structure: eight sections, precise timing

Eight distinct sections appear across virtually every high-converting agency VSL. The Conversionly 8-step framework, Cole Gordon's Closers.io structure, and the Roezan "simple 5-minute VSL" all converge on these same building blocks — differing only in emphasis and pacing. Here is the synthesized master structure with timing benchmarks for a B2B agency VSL targeting eCom/supplement brands:

**Section 1 — The Hook + Audience Callout (0:00–0:30).** Grab attention within **5 seconds**. Pattern-interrupt the viewer, call out exactly who this is for, and tease the big promise. Psychologically, this exploits the curiosity gap — the brain finds unresolved information uncomfortable and must keep watching. Eighty-five percent of viewers decide to stay or leave in this window.

**Section 2 — The Big Claim + Guarantee (0:30–1:15).** State a specific, measurable, time-bound result with a risk-reversal guarantee attached. This is not the pitch — it is the "reason to keep watching." The specificity of numbers triggers an automatic assumption of truthfulness. Break the claim into **three clear steps** of what you will do to achieve it. Example framing: "If you're an eCom or supplement brand doing $50K+/month, we can add $50K–$150K in annual email revenue in the next 90 days — or we refund every dollar."

**Section 3 — Problem Identification + Agitation (1:15–3:30).** Articulate their pain better than they can articulate it themselves. Use their exact language — mined from Reddit r/ecommerce, Klaviyo community forums, and recorded sales calls. Then twist the knife: quantify the cost of inaction, show compounding consequences, and paint a vivid picture of the deteriorating future. Loss aversion is **2x more powerful** than the pleasure of gain.

**Section 4 — Credibility + Social Proof (3:30–5:00).** Present 2–3 mini case studies with specific before/after numbers. Each case study should hit a **different pain point** that mirrors different viewer situations. Follow with a rapid-fire stack of 3–5 additional results to demonstrate consistency. Transition language: "Now, how can I make a promise like this? Look at my track record…"

**Section 5 — First CTA (5:00–5:15).** Soft call-to-action: "If that's all you need to hear, click below to book a call. However, if you want to know the ONE REASON this works so well… keep watching." This creates an open loop while capturing early converters. The Roezan template and Cole Gordon framework both include this mid-VSL CTA — most viewers will not make it to the end, so **never wait until the final minute**.

**Section 6 — The Unique Mechanism (5:15–7:30).** Explain WHY your method is different, unique, and superior to what they have tried before. Name your proprietary framework. Contrast against competitors ("generic email agencies that blast your whole list with discount codes") and against DIY ("you don't have the 10–15 hours per week or the Klaviyo expertise"). This is the section that transforms your VSL from "another agency pitch" into something genuinely new.

**Section 7 — Objection Handling + Second CTA (7:30–9:00).** Pre-emptively address the top 3–5 objections: "I've tried email before and it didn't work," "Agencies are expensive," "I don't have time for this," "How long until results?" Then deliver the second CTA with a bonus for booking (free email audit, revenue roadmap PDF).

**Section 8 — Value Stack + Urgency + Final CTA (9:00–10:30).** Stack the value of the call itself (not your service — the call). Eliminate risk. Future-pace the positive outcome. Then contrast with the negative future if they do nothing. Create real urgency with capacity scarcity. Close with explicit instructions: "Click the button below, pick a time, and let's build your revenue roadmap together."

| Section | Duration | Psychological Function |
|---------|----------|----------------------|
| Hook + Callout | 0:00–0:30 | Pattern interrupt, self-selection |
| Big Claim + Guarantee | 0:30–1:15 | Cognitive dissonance, belief suspension |
| Problem + Agitation | 1:15–3:30 | Empathy, loss aversion, urgency to solve |
| Credibility + Proof | 3:30–5:00 | Trust transfer, social proof |
| First CTA | 5:00–5:15 | Capture early converters, create open loop |
| Unique Mechanism | 5:15–7:30 | Differentiation, new hope |
| Objections + Second CTA | 7:30–9:00 | Doubt resolution, friction removal |
| Value Stack + Urgency + Close | 9:00–10:30 | Desire crystallization, action trigger |

