## 2. Six hook formulas that stop the scroll in 5 seconds

The opening 15 seconds are binary — viewers stay or leave. The strongest hooks combine at least two psychological triggers simultaneously: pattern interruption (breaking expected flow), curiosity gap (creating information voids), and self-selection (making the right people feel personally targeted). Here are six proven formulas with niche-specific examples:

**The Curiosity Hook.** Formula: "[Unexpected claim] that [specific audience] are using to [desirable outcome]… and [most people] don't even know it exists." Example: *"There's a 3-email sequence that supplement brand owners are quietly using to turn $1 buyers into $247 repeat customers — and 97% of eCom brands have never heard of it."* Works best for sophisticated audiences who think they've seen everything.

**The Bold Claim Hook.** Formula: "How [specific avatar] can [achieve specific result] in [timeframe] without [biggest objection]." Example: *"How we helped a supplement brand go from $27,000 to $250,000 in monthly email revenue in under 90 days — without sending a single discount code, adding a single new subscriber, or writing 'Hey {first_name}' ever again."* Requires rock-solid proof to back it up.

**The Story Hook.** Formula: "[Time marker] ago, [client] was [relatable painful situation]… [emotional detail]… and then [unexpected discovery]." Example: *"Eight months ago, I got on a call with a supplement brand doing $2.3 million a year. They were spending $40K a month on Meta ads, and their email list of 85,000 subscribers was generating less than $6,000 a month. The founder told me, 'I feel like I'm sitting on a gold mine but I'm using a plastic spoon to dig.' What happened over the next 90 days changed everything."* Storytelling bypasses the logical "sales resistance" filter entirely — neural coupling makes the listener's brain mirror the storyteller's brain activity.

**The Pattern Interrupt Hook.** Formula: "[Shocking contrarian statement]… [pause]… [clarifying reframe]." Example: *"Stop sending emails to your customers. Seriously. Because what most eCom brands call 'email marketing' is actually organized spam — and it's costing you between $30,000 and $500,000 a year in revenue you should already be collecting."* Use when you have a genuinely contrarian perspective; the interrupt must connect logically to your content or viewers feel baited.

**The "Who This Is For" Hook.** Formula: "If you [qualifier — who they are + situation], and you [second qualifier — frustration or desire], then [what this video will do]." Example: *"If you're an eCom or supplement brand owner doing $50K to $5M per month, and you know your email list should be generating way more revenue than it is — but you're stuck in a cycle of blasting promos that get ignored, working with freelancers who ghost you, or paying an agency that sends 'pretty reports' with zero actual profit — then what I'm about to show you in the next 11 minutes will change everything."* This is the **safest, most reliable default** for B2B agency VSLs.

**The Proof-First Hook.** Formula: "[Specific result] for [specific client type] in [specific timeframe]. Here's exactly how." Example: *"$143,000 in email revenue in 30 days. That's what our newest eCom supplement client generated from a list that was doing $11,000 the month before we started. No new subscribers. No new products. No discounts. Just a completely rebuilt email system."* Best when you have extraordinary, verifiable numbers.

