## 7. Closing the VSL: the CTA that gets calls booked

The CTA section follows a precise seven-part sequence: value recap/stack, risk reversal, positive future pacing, negative future pacing (contrast), urgency/scarcity, clear specific instructions, and a one-line final reinforcement. Three CTAs appear throughout the VSL — a soft CTA at ~40%, a medium CTA at ~65%, and the full hard close at ~90%.

**The value stack sells the CALL, not the service.** Unlike product VSLs where you assign dollar values to bonuses, for a booking-call VSL you stack the value of the call itself: *"On this call, we'll audit your current email setup — something agencies charge $500–$1,000 for. We'll identify your 3 biggest email revenue leaks. And we'll build you a custom 90-day Email Revenue Roadmap you can implement yourself — whether you work with us or not."*

**Critical naming insight from Adstra (50,000+ leads generated): never call it a "discovery call" or "strategy session."** Name it something with inherent value. For an email marketing agency: "Email Revenue Audit," "Revenue Leak Analysis," "Lifecycle Revenue Diagnostic." The name alone should communicate that the call delivers value independent of whether they become a client.

**Risk reversal for free calls targets time and vulnerability, not money.** The prospect fears being sold to, wasting time, or being judged for poor performance. Address all three: *"This isn't a high-pressure sales call. We'll show you the gaps, give you the plan, and if it makes sense for both of us, we'll talk about working together. If not, you keep everything."* The most powerful technique is **qualifying them** (reversing the dynamic): "We only take on 4 new clients per month, so this call is actually for us to see if we're a fit for YOUR brand."

**Urgency must be real.** For agencies, use capacity scarcity ("We only onboard 4 new brands per month — 2 spots currently open"), calendar scarcity ("7 slots open this week; next availability is in 2 weeks"), seasonal urgency ("Q4 is 11 weeks away — brands that start now will capture the revenue"), and opportunity cost framing ("Every day without optimized flows = $X,000 in unrealized revenue").

**Value-based CTA language outperforms generic language by 327%.** Write "See how much revenue YOUR list is leaving on the table" or "Get your free Email Revenue Audit" — not "Schedule a call" or "Contact us." The CTA instruction should be explicit: "Click the button below this video right now. Pick a time that works for you. And let's build your revenue roadmap together."

