## 9. What top-performing agency VSLs all have in common

Analysis of VSL structures from King Kong/Sabri Suby, Cole Gordon's Closers.io ($25M+ attributed), Client Ascension ($5M+ from VSLs), and multiple eCom/SMMA agencies reveals seven universal elements that appear in every high-performer:

**Hyper-specific audience callout within the first 10 seconds.** Never "business owners" — always "supplement brands doing $50K–$500K/month." The narrower the callout, the higher the conversion among the right audience.

**A specific, measurable, time-bound claim.** Not "we'll grow your email revenue" but "we'll add $50K–$150K in annual email revenue within 90 days." The claim IS the VSL — as the Roezan analysis concluded: *"The REAL trick is the OFFER. If this script doesn't work, it's not because of the structure. It's because the claim/offer aren't good enough."*

**A named unique mechanism that explains WHY.** Every successful agency VSL has a proprietary framework that differentiates from "we write better emails." This mechanism explains past failures and gives new hope.

**Proof before pitch, always.** Case studies and results appear BEFORE the offer details in every top-performing structure. Sabri Suby's approach explicitly teaches "sell like a doctor — diagnose before you prescribe."

**Multiple CTAs starting no later than 40% through.** The first CTA is soft ("If that's all you need to hear, click below"), creating an open loop for those who keep watching while capturing early converters.

**Real urgency tied to operational capacity.** Capacity scarcity ("We only onboard 4 brands per month") outperforms artificial countdown timers. eCom brand owners are sophisticated enough to detect manufactured urgency.

**Brevity.** For call-booking VSLs, **8–12 minutes consistently outperforms** longer formats. The rare exception is when the VSL doubles as an educational piece for cold traffic, where 15–20 minutes can work.

