## 11. The pre-call VSL: converting booked calls into closed deals

The pre-call VSL is structurally and psychologically distinct from the landing page VSL. Its purpose is not to generate bookings — that is already done. Its purpose is to **increase show-up rates** (agencies report **90%+ show rates** with proper pre-call nurture vs. 50–60% without), pre-sell the prospect so the sales call becomes "order-taking" rather than pitching, and pre-handle objections so the rep doesn't start from scratch.

Daniel Fazio of Client Ascension ($5M+ attributed to VSLs) explains: *"By the time they're on the phone, they've already heard your pitch, seen your evidence, understood your value proposition, and had most of their objections addressed. Your sales call just morphed into an order-taking call."*

**Ideal length: 15–20 minutes** for high-ticket agency services. The prospect has already committed by booking, so they are more invested and will tolerate longer content.

**The six-section pre-call VSL structure.** Minutes 0–2: Thank them for booking, frame why they should watch the entire video, promise a specific takeaway regardless of whether they become a client. Minutes 2–5: Brief origin story and credibility — specific results, number of brands served, total revenue generated. Minutes 5–9: Articulate their pain points in their exact language, name what they've tried before, explain WHY those approaches failed (introducing the mechanism). Minutes 9–13: Present your proprietary framework at a high level with 2–3 detailed case studies. Minutes 13–16: Set call expectations ("Here's exactly what will happen on our call"), pre-handle the top objections, address cost preemptively ("The investment typically pays for itself within 30–60 days"). Minutes 16–18: Logistics and prep instructions ("Have your Klaviyo login available, know your monthly revenue and list size"), create excitement about the call.

**Key differences from the landing page VSL.** The tone shifts from urgent and pattern-interrupt to warm, personal, and consultative. The goal shifts from "book a call" to "show up ready to buy." Objection handling becomes thorough rather than brief. Social proof becomes detailed case studies (building trust) rather than headline numbers (creating desire). Production should show your face — on-camera is preferred for trust-building.

**The show-up rate maximization sequence:** Auto-play the pre-call VSL on the booking confirmation page. Send it via email within minutes (subject: "Watch this before our call on [date]"). Deploy multi-channel reminders: email at 24 hours, SMS at 1 hour, personal video message at 10 minutes. Give "homework" — a brief questionnaire that makes them invest thought.

